# How Does Music Influence Mood and Behaviour?  
## A Comprehensive Scientific Report

---

## Introduction

Music is a universal human experience that has been part of societies for millennia. Its profound impact on human mood and behaviour is widely acknowledged, yet the underlying mechanisms have only been rigorously studied in recent decades. Advances in neuroscience, psychology, and physiology have begun to elucidate how music affects emotional states, cognitive functions, and social behaviours. This report synthesizes current scientific evidence to provide an in-depth understanding of how music influences mood and behaviour, emphasizing neurochemical pathways, psychological processes, and physiological responses.

---

## 1. Psychological Functions of Music Listening

### 1.1 Primary Reasons for Listening to Music

A 2013 psychological survey identified three main reasons people listen to music:

- Regulating mood and stress (arousal)
- Achieving self-awareness
- Expressing social relatedness

The first two reasons—mood regulation and self-awareness—were found to be more important than social expression. Music is often used as a personal tool for motivation, focus, and stress relief, either in the foreground or as background sound ([The Psychological Functions of Music Listening, 2013](https://www.frontiersin.org/articles/10.3389/fpsyg.2013.00511/full)).

### 1.2 Cross-Cultural Emotional Perception

Studies show that listeners across diverse cultures can identify basic emotional valences in unfamiliar music. For example, Western listeners could discern happiness or sadness in Navajo, Kyrghistani, and Hindustani music, while a remote tribe in Cameroon identified happiness or sadness in Western music. Common features such as tempo and volume (slow/soft = sadness; fast/jaunty = happiness) appear universal in emotional interpretation ([Science Museum Blog, 2018](https://www.sciencemuseum.org.uk/objects-and-stories/how-music-affects-mood)).

