## 4. Music’s Influence on Behaviour

### 4.1 Cognitive Performance and Creativity

Moderate ambient noise (~70 dB) or music without lyrics can enhance creativity and productivity by providing optimal arousal without distraction. However, louder noise reduces creativity due to increased distraction ([Mehta et al., 2012](https://academic.oup.com/jcr/article/39/5/1137/1829140)).

### 4.2 Social Affiliation and Oxytocin

Music fosters social bonding through synchronized activities like group singing or drumming, which increase oxytocin levels—a neuropeptide linked to trust and social affiliation. Elevated oxytocin during musical activities correlates with feelings of social connection and reduced stress ([Nilsson, 2009](https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/full/10.1111/j.1365-2702.2009.02808.x)).

### 4.3 Behavioural Regulation and Emotional Expression

Different genres of music can evoke or regulate specific behaviours and emotions. For example:

- **Rap and R&B:** Can calm or empower listeners, influencing mood and sometimes aggressive behaviour depending on lyrical content ([Slaton et al., 2012](https://prezi.com/)).
- **Classical and Jazz:** Often used for relaxation and focus.
- **Upbeat Pop/Rock:** Enhances motivation and energy, useful in exercise or work contexts ([British Band Instrument Company, 2017](https://britishband.co.uk/)).

